{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17515612","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17515612"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:33:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:33:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12462"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12462","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12462"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.37,0.12,0.09,0.26]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4970"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107219"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4970","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4970"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12462"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89674"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"81"},{"type":"tags","id":"88"},{"type":"tags","id":"483"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"2283"},{"type":"tags","id":"2400"},{"type":"tags","id":"2701"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8183"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9527"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32491"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33086"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39834"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107219","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107219"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 48-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a seven-day history of productive cough, fever, and progressive shortness of breath. His medical history includes chronic obstructive pulmonary disease and poorly controlled diabetes mellitus. His regular medications are salbutamol as needed, fluticasone/salmeterol inhaler, and metformin. He has a 20 pack-year smoking history and works as a farmer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 105/min, blood pressure 135/89 mmHg, respiratory rate 25/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 38.3\u00b0C. Chest examination reveals diffuse crackles and wheezing throughout both lung fields.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EWhite cell count: 14.5 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EC-reactive protein: 180 mg/L (\u003C5)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EChest X-ray: bilateral patchy infiltrates\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EBlood cultures and sputum samples have been collected but no causative organism has been identified\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has received three days of empirical ceftriaxone and azithromycin with nebulised bronchodilators with minimal improvement in his symptoms. A repeat chest X-ray shows no significant change from the initial film.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT chest with contrast","Bronchoscopy with bronchoalveolar lavage","Change to a different antibiotic regimen","Add an antiviral medication","Commence empirical antifungal therapy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with non-resolving pneumonia despite three days of appropriate empirical antibiotic therapy with ceftriaxone and azithromycin. Several risk factors for atypical or fungal pneumonia are present, including poorly controlled diabetes mellitus, COPD, and occupational exposure as a farmer. When standard therapy fails to produce clinical improvement, further diagnostic testing is warranted to identify the causative organism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBronchoscopy with bronchoalveolar lavage\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step as it allows direct visualisation of the airways and collection of fluid samples for microbiological analysis. This procedure is particularly valuable for diagnosing atypical bacterial, fungal, or mycobacterial infections that may not be detected through routine sputum cultures. In this patient with risk factors for fungal pneumonia (diabetes, COPD, occupational exposure), bronchoscopy provides the best opportunity to establish a specific diagnosis and guide targeted therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT chest with contrast\u003C/strong\u003E would provide more detailed anatomical information than chest X-ray and could identify complications such as empyema, lung abscess, or cavitation. However, while CT may better characterise the extent of disease, it would not identify the specific pathogen causing the pneumonia, which is the critical information needed to guide further management at this stage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChange to a different antibiotic regimen\u003C/strong\u003E without identifying the causative organism would be a suboptimal approach. While empirical therapy is appropriate initially, the failure to respond after three days warrants a diagnostic approach rather than simply changing antibiotics blindly. Identifying the specific pathogen would allow for targeted antimicrobial therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdd an antiviral medication\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate without evidence suggesting a viral aetiology. The clinical presentation and investigation findings are more consistent with bacterial or fungal pneumonia rather than viral pneumonia, and there are no specific features mentioned that would suggest a viral cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence empirical antifungal therapy\u003C/strong\u003E might be tempting given the patient\u0027s risk factors for fungal pneumonia. However, antifungal medications have significant side effects and drug interactions. Starting empirical antifungal therapy without microbiological confirmation would be premature when a diagnostic procedure (bronchoscopy) is available that could provide a definitive diagnosis within 24-48 hours.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Bronchoscopy with bronchoalveolar lavage is the investigation of choice for non-resolving pneumonia, particularly when atypical or fungal causes are suspected.","Uncontrolled diabetes, COPD, and occupational exposures (such as farming) are risk factors for fungal pneumonia.","Empirical antibiotic therapy should be reassessed if pneumonia fails to improve after 72 hours of appropriate treatment."],"references":["Fort\u00fan J. Diagnostic and therapeutic approach to fungal pneumonia in the critically ill patient. Rev Esp Quimioter. 2022;35 Suppl 1(Suppl 1):97-103. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35488836/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89674"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12462"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89674","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89674"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-26T14:24:03+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-26T14:27:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4970"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107219"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":nul